JavaScript's built-in `confirm` method does not allow customization of button labels. However, you can mimic a confirm dialog with HTML and CSS for full control, including using Danish text. Here's an example implementing a custom dialog:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="da">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Custom Confirm Dialog</title>
    <style>
        #custom-confirm {
            display: none;
            position: fixed;
            left: 0;
            top: 0;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .dialog {
            background: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            text-align: center;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="custom-confirm">
    <div class="dialog">
        <p>Vil du udskrive fakturaen?</p>
        <button onclick="handleResponse(true)">Ja</button>
        <button onclick="handleResponse(false)">Nej</button>
    </div>
</div>

<script>
function showConfirmDialog() {
    document.getElementById('custom-confirm').style.display = 'flex';
}

function handleResponse(isConfirmed) {
    document.getElementById('custom-confirm').style.display = 'none';
    if (isConfirmed) {
        window.print();
    }
}

// Example usage
showConfirmDialog();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This code includes a custom confirm dialog that lets you display Danish text and handle user responses accordingly.

